litics and communication questions many of the conventional ways in which children are perceived. It focuses on the politics of children's communication, in two senses: children as political actors, and the micropolitics of children's interaction with each other and with adults. It looks at how children and young people communicate and engage, how they organise themselves and their lives, and how they deal with conflict in their relationships and the world around them. These are children at the margins, in various ways, but they are not victims; they are finding ways to take charge of their own lives. The book is also about adults and how they can interact with children and young people in ways that are sensitive to children's feelings, empowering and supportive of their attempts to be autonomous. With international contributions from a range of disciplines, Children, politics and communication is timely and relevant for policy makers, practitioners and researchers engaging with children and young people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChild psychology. 0aChildren and adults. 0aChildrenxServices for. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aChurch, Amelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawley, Heaven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHua, Zhu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Vicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohli, Ravi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaynard, Trisha,